---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import PrivateHeader from "../../components/PrivateHeader.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout noindex={true} title="Amex / Katie Interview Prep | Leigh-Ann Martin" description="Chief of Staff round prep for the Senior EA role at American Express: top objections from Katie, the mindset reframe, and why you're the top candidate.">
  <PrivateHeader />
  <div class="md:ml-60">
  <main>
    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="bg-primary pt-24 pb-12 md:pt-16 md:pb-16">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-secondary mb-4">Chief of Staff Round</p>
        <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-white leading-tight mb-4">
          Interview with Katie Fitzgerald Braunstein
          <span class="block text-white/55 text-2xl md:text-3xl mt-2">American Express &middot; Chief of Staff</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="text-white/55 text-base leading-relaxed max-w-xl mx-auto mb-6">
          Tomorrow, 2026-06-04, on WebEx. This is the companion to your full Sachin dossier &mdash; tightened for one job: win Katie, defuse her concerns, and make it obvious you're the one she should send forward. Refine, don't rebuild.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-2">
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Tomorrow</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Sachin liked your resume</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">6-candidate field</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Referral: Sai</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">WebEx &mdash; clean background</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Quick Nav -->
    <section class="bg-primary/95 border-t border-white/[0.06] py-4 sticky top-14 md:top-0 z-40">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-2 text-xs">
          <a href="#cheat-card" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">Cheat Card</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#status" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">1. Where You Stand</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#katie" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">2. Who Is Katie</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#mindset" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">3. Mindset</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#objections" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">4. Objections</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#commitment" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">5. Commitment</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#standout" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">6. Why You</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#blue-box" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">7. Blue Box</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#questions" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">8. Ask Katie</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#checklist" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">9. Delivery</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Cheat Card -->
    <section id="cheat-card" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Re-read 30 Minutes Before</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">The TL;DR Cheat Card</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-6">If you only re-read one thing before the WebEx call, make it this card.</p>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 space-y-5">
          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">Where you stand</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm leading-relaxed">Katie put six candidates in front of Sachin and <span class="font-medium">Sachin singled out your resume</span>. The recruiter gave positive feedback. You're not auditioning cold &mdash; you're the candidate the principal already preferred. Katie is the one round between you and the finish line. Win her.</p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">The one thing to land</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm italic leading-relaxed">"I'm here to take the weight off Katie's plate and stay put while I do it." Every answer should ladder to one of two ideas: <span class="font-medium not-italic">I make your life easier</span>, and <span class="font-medium not-italic">I'm building for the long run, not a stepping stone.</span></p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">3 stories to lead with</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Ascend board cadence from zero</span>: you walk into under-structured rooms and build order &mdash; exactly Katie's situation right now.</li>
              <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Earnings-prep system rebuild</span>: you turn heroics into a repeatable system, so the principal stops firefighting.</li>
              <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Immunovant: sole EA to 5 C-suite, onboarded 6 admin pros (~20% ramp cut)</span>: you carry load solo <em>and</em> bring order to a team.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">Your "why I'll stay" line (say it once, naturally)</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm leading-relaxed">"I've done EVP-level work across several seats. What I want now isn't another rung &mdash; it's <span class="font-medium">depth</span>: one principal, one org I get to know cold, where mastering the seat is the win. That's the kind of role I stay in and build."</p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">If the "too ambitious" worry surfaces</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm leading-relaxed">Don't shrink. <span class="font-medium">Redirect the ambition onto her outcomes:</span> "I'm driven, yes &mdash; about making the person I support look great and the work run flawlessly. That energy goes into the seat, not past it."</p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">Delivery reminders</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm leading-relaxed"><span class="font-medium">Clean, natural background</span> (no virtual background &mdash; WebEx makes them distracting). <span class="font-medium">Slow down by a third</span>, headline first, pause for two seconds after big statements. Concise and solution-focused &mdash; diagnose before you prescribe.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 1. Where You Stand -->
    <section id="status" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 1</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Where You Stand in the Process</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-6">Read this first so you walk in from a position of strength. Every claim below is sourced from Sai's June 3 call.</p>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 mb-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-base mb-3">The signals are good</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Katie shortlisted six candidates</span> for Sachin, and <span class="font-medium text-primary">Sachin specifically liked your resume</span> <span class="inline-block bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Confirmed (Sai)</span>. The decision-maker already leans your way.</li>
            <li>The <span class="font-medium text-primary">recruiter shared positive feedback</span> in follow-ups after your screening <span class="inline-block bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Confirmed (Sai)</span>.</li>
            <li>Your meeting with Katie reportedly <span class="font-medium text-primary">dispelled some of her earlier concerns</span> already <span class="inline-block bg-amber-100 text-amber-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Likely</span>. Tomorrow is about closing the gap, not starting over.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 mb-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-base mb-3">The remaining steps</h3>
          <ol class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted list-decimal list-inside">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Katie Fitzgerald Braunstein, Chief of Staff</span> &mdash; tomorrow <span class="inline-block bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Confirmed (Sai)</span>.</li>
            <li>The <span class="font-medium text-primary">Amex HR-partner equivalent</span> (Amex uses an internal term for this role) <span class="inline-block bg-amber-100 text-amber-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Likely</span>.</li>
            <li>Another executive close to Sachin &mdash; <span class="font-medium text-primary">likely the VP of Consumer Digital Tech</span>, who also has an EA and may be covering some support for Sachin during the search <span class="inline-block bg-amber-100 text-amber-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Likely</span>. They're close collaborators, so a strong word from them carries weight.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-secondary/5 border border-secondary/15 rounded-xl p-5">
          <p class="text-sm text-primary"><span class="font-semibold">Carry this posture:</span> <span class="text-text-muted">You are not starting cold with Katie &mdash; you are the candidate the principal already preferred. Walk in like it, quietly. Confident, warm, here to help her, not here to be judged.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 2. Who Is Katie -->
    <section id="katie" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 2</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Who Is Katie &mdash; and What a CoS Needs From an EA</h2>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 mb-6">
          <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-base">Katie Fitzgerald Braunstein</h3>
            <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/katiefitzbraun/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-secondary text-xs underline hover:no-underline">LinkedIn &rarr;</a>
          </div>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Chief of Staff to Sachin</span>, and the person who built the candidate shortlist <span class="inline-block bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Confirmed (Sai)</span>.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">New to the CoS role &mdash; roughly a month in</span> <span class="inline-block bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Confirmed (Sai)</span>. She's still building her own footing while she hires.</li>
            <li>The <span class="font-medium text-primary">previous EA left after 2 years</span> (moved to a new role), and the current manager/assistant is <span class="font-medium text-primary">on a PIP and out on medical leave</span> <span class="inline-block bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Confirmed (Sai)</span>.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Katie is running everything solo right now.</span> The need is real and urgent &mdash; she is underwater and looking for relief <span class="inline-block bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Confirmed (Sai)</span>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">What a Chief of Staff actually needs from an EA</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li>A Chief of Staff is the executive's force-multiplier. <span class="font-medium text-primary">A great EA is the Chief of Staff's force-multiplier.</span> Katie's win is getting hours back so she can do the strategic CoS work only she can do.</li>
            <li>She needs someone who can take the calendar, the inbox triage, the meeting prep, and the operational follow-through <span class="font-medium text-primary">off her plate without supervision</span> &mdash; not someone she has to manage on top of everything else.</li>
            <li>She needs trust and discretion fast. The seat sits next to an EVP's confidential work &mdash; board-adjacent, partner-facing, sometimes sensitive. <span class="font-medium text-primary">Frame yourself as relief, not rivalry.</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-secondary/5 border border-secondary/15 rounded-xl p-5">
          <p class="text-sm text-primary"><span class="font-semibold">Why this is your single biggest opening:</span> <span class="text-text-muted">Katie's situation &mdash; brand-new, solo, no structure, urgent &mdash; is the <em>exact</em> situation you've walked into and fixed before. You built Ascend's board cadence from zero and stood up the Immunovant EA function from nothing. Don't just claim you can handle chaos; name that this is the work you're best at. "From what Sai shared, you're holding a lot solo right now. That's genuinely the situation I do my best work in &mdash; walking into something under-structured and quietly making it run."</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 3. Mindset -->
    <section id="mindset" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 3 &middot; Read This For You, Not Just the Interview</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Mindset: Your Ambition Is the Asset</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-6">When someone signals you're "too ambitious" or "too strong," it's easy to hear "be smaller." Don't. The strength that built a board cadence from zero is the exact thing a drowning, brand-new Chief of Staff needs. The work isn't to dial yourself down &mdash; it's to <span class="font-medium">point the same strength at her outcomes</span>.</p>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 mb-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-base mb-3">Two kinds of ambition &mdash; and only one is a risk to them</h3>
          <div class="space-y-4 text-sm">
            <div>
              <p class="text-primary font-medium mb-1">Ambition-for-impact <span class="inline-block bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">Asset</span></p>
              <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">"I want this seat to be excellent. I want Sachin's week to run flawlessly and Katie to look great." This is the energy every executive wants beside them. Lead with it.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="text-primary font-medium mb-1">Ambition-to-leave <span class="inline-block bg-rose-100 text-rose-800 text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded ml-1">The fear</span></p>
              <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">"I'll use this as a stepping stone to something bigger." This is what they're afraid "ambitious" means. You never name it &mdash; you just make sure nothing you say accidentally signals it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">Three tells that project the first, not the second</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">1. Diagnose before you prescribe.</span> Ask one question about her situation before you launch into a strength. It signals you serve the need in front of you, not a personal agenda.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">2. Anchor every strength to <em>her</em> life getting easier.</span> Not "I built a board cadence from zero" full stop, but "&hellip;so the executive stopped firefighting every quarter." The accomplishment is the proof; <em>their</em> relief is the point.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">3. Talk depth, not trajectory.</span> When the future comes up, reach for mastery of <em>this</em> seat &mdash; knowing the org cold, becoming indispensable &mdash; not the next title up. Mastery reads as commitment; trajectory reads as flight risk.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-secondary/5 border border-secondary/15 rounded-xl p-5">
          <p class="text-sm text-primary"><span class="font-semibold">A note worth holding onto:</span> <span class="text-text-muted">The work you did rebuilding your own profile since 2024 &mdash; naming your real impact at these companies out loud &mdash; was true. The impact was real. If a room reads that strength as "threatening," that's a signal about <em>fit in that moment</em>, not a verdict on your worth. Tomorrow, the move isn't to hide the strength. It's to make it unmistakably clear the strength is <em>in service of them</em>. That's how a strong candidate becomes the obvious hire instead of an intimidating one.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 4. Objections -->
    <section id="objections" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 4 &middot; The Core</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Top Objections From Katie &amp; How to Overcome Them</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-6">Each card: what Katie is likely thinking, the counter-strategy, and a specific line or story to deploy. Don't recite these &mdash; absorb the posture and make the words your own.</p>

        <div class="space-y-4">

          <!-- Obj 1: flight risk internal -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
              <h3 class="font-serif text-lg text-primary">"She'll leave &mdash; transfer internally to another role."</h3>
              <span class="text-xs bg-rose-100 text-rose-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full whitespace-nowrap">High &mdash; stated</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic mb-3"><span class="font-semibold not-italic text-primary">What Katie's thinking:</span> This is the Amex side's explicit worry &mdash; not that you'll quit, but that you'll use the EA seat as a doorway into a different internal role and leave them re-hiring in a year. The last EA left after two years; she can't afford a short stay during a transition she's already running solo.</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Counter-strategy:</span> Name what <em>this</em> seat gives you that a jump wouldn't: depth, a principal worth knowing cold, an org at real scale. Point to your tenure pattern &mdash; multi-year stays where you stayed to <em>run</em> what you built &mdash; not a string of short hops. Make "I'm choosing depth here" the through-line.</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-xs text-primary font-semibold mb-1">Line to deploy:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"I've supported executives across several seats now. What I'm looking for isn't variety &mdash; it's one principal and one org I can know cold and build around. At Immunovant I stayed three years and ran the program I built; at Ascend I stood up the board cadence and saw it through. <span class="font-medium not-italic text-primary">When the seat is the right one, I build for the long run, not the next step.</span>"</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Obj 2: too ambitious / wants her seat -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
              <h3 class="font-serif text-lg text-primary">"She's too ambitious &mdash; will she be content as an EA, or want my seat?"</h3>
              <span class="text-xs bg-rose-100 text-rose-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full whitespace-nowrap">High &mdash; Katie</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic mb-3"><span class="font-semibold not-italic text-primary">What Katie's thinking:</span> Your profile is strong &mdash; board governance, public-company IR, building functions from zero. A brand-new Chief of Staff, still finding her own footing, can read a strong EA as a threat: will this person be satisfied in the role, or angling for mine?</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Counter-strategy:</span> Don't shrink the strength &mdash; redirect it. Your ambition is <em>for the work and the person you support</em>, not past them. The CoS and EA win together: you make her look great, you don't compete with her. Show service, warmth, and zero status-seeking.</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-xs text-primary font-semibold mb-1">Line to deploy:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"I'm driven &mdash; I won't pretend otherwise. But it's drive aimed at one thing: making the person I support look excellent and the operation run without friction. The reason I've built board cadences and onboarding systems isn't to climb &mdash; it's because I can't help making the seat around an executive work better. <span class="font-medium not-italic text-primary">That energy goes into the role, not past it.</span> When you look good, I've done my job."</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Obj 3: fractional commit -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
              <h3 class="font-serif text-lg text-primary">"Fractional background &mdash; will she commit to one principal, 4 days in office?"</h3>
              <span class="text-xs bg-rose-100 text-rose-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full whitespace-nowrap">High</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic mb-3"><span class="font-semibold not-italic text-primary">What Katie's thinking:</span> Recent multi-client work can read as flighty. This is a single-principal, mostly-in-office job at Amex's revenue engine. Will you actually show up, week after week?</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Counter-strategy:</span> Reframe fractional as deliberate skill-stacking, not flightiness. You've been doing EVP-level work across several seats and are choosing now to compound it into one. Name it before she has to ask.</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-xs text-primary font-semibold mb-1">Line to deploy:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"My fractional years were deliberate &mdash; they gave me the EVP playbook from several seats at once. What I want now is the opposite of spread: one principal, at scale, where I go deep. <span class="font-medium not-italic text-primary">When the work is meaningful and the seat is right, I build for the long run.</span>"</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Obj 4: solo load -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
              <h3 class="font-serif text-lg text-primary">"Can she carry the load solo while we're underwater?"</h3>
              <span class="text-xs bg-amber-100 text-amber-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full whitespace-nowrap">Likely</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic mb-3"><span class="font-semibold not-italic text-primary">What Katie's thinking:</span> She's running everything alone right now and needs someone who lightens the load on day one, not someone who needs heavy onboarding while she's already stretched.</p>
